Part I - (Prosper Loan Data)¶

by Nolwazi Mlala¶

Introduction¶

In this document, we examine a dataset containing 113,937 loans with 81 variables for each loan: loan amount, borrower's interest rate (or rate), current loan status, borrower's income, etc.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset contains 113,937 loans and 81 characteristics. The majority of variables are category and numerical in character.

There are two primary categories of features in the dataset:

Borrower details information about loan performance

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

Finding out which borrower characteristics can most accurately forecast a high rate of return is what I'm most interested in learning as an investor.

How closely did the estimated and actual loan performance match up?

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Though there are many features to explore, I suspect the following borrower features will have the largest effect on the performance of the loan:

IncomeRange - The income range of the borrower at the time the listing was created. DebToIncomeRatio - The debt to income ratio of the borrower at the time the credit profile was pulled. This value is Null if the debt to income ratio is not available. This value is capped at 10.01 (any debt to income ratio larger than 1000% will be returned as 1001%). CreditGrade - The Credit rating that was assigned at the time the listing went live. Applicable for listings pre-2009 period and will only be populated for those listings. ProsperRating (Alpha) - The Prosper Rating assigned at the time the listing was created between AA - HR. Applicable for loans originated after July 2009.

def Split_String(string):
    
    return ''.join([x if x.islower() else f' {x}' for x in string])
In [10]:
def CountPlot_x(df, xVar, color = 0, order = None, figsize = figsize):
    
    '''
    This function takes:
       df - pandas data frame
       xVar - the variables to be shown on the x-axis
       color, order and fig size have default values for color, order and figure size
       
       >>> Returns a count plot with vertical bars

    '''
    
    
    plt.figure(figsize = figsize);
    sns.countplot(data = df, x = xVar, edgecolor = None, color = sns.color_palette()[color], order = order)
    xVar = Split_String(xVar).replace('_', '')
    plt.title(f'''Distribution of {xVar}'''.title(), fontsize = 12, weight = 'bold')
    plt.xlabel(xVar.title(), fontsize = 10, weight = 'bold')
    plt.ylabel('Count'.title(), fontsize = 10, weight = 'bold')
    plt.xticks(rotation = 90)
    return plt.show()

From the feature descriptions, it looks like Prosper transitioned to a "Prosper Rating" after 2009 to differentiate themselves from the industry standard "Credit Grade.

For exploratory purposes, we'll replace the Credit Grade of No Credit (NC) with High Risk (HR) and combine this column with the Prosper Rating.

In the future we may want to look at estimated returns of the pre-2009 "Credit Grade" to see how it compares with the post-2009 "Prosper Rating" to validate if they truly are equivalent or if Prosper skewed their credit rating in some way.

def CountPlot_y(df, yVar, palette = 0,order = None, figsize= (8,5)):
    '''
    *Args:
    df - dataframe
    yVar - y-variables
    palette - default = 0
    order - default = none
    figsize = default = (8,5)
    >>> Returns count plot with vertical bars
    '''
    plt.figure(figsize = figsize);
    sns.countplot(data = df, y = yVar, edgecolor = None, palette=palette,  order = order)
    yVar = Split_String(yVar).replace('_', '')
    plt.title(f'''Distribution of {yVar}'''.title(), fontsize = 12, weight = 'bold')
    plt.xlabel('Count'.title(), fontsize = 10, weight = 'bold')
    plt.ylabel(yVar.title(), fontsize = 10, weight = 'bold')
    
    return plt.show()

Qualitative vs. Qualitiative¶

Let's continue to explore this thread by also plotting the credit score along with the income range.

In [30]:
# clustered bar chart
plt.figure(figsize = [10,8])

ax = sns.countplot(data = df, y = 'IncomeRange', hue = 'ProsperRatingCombined',
                   palette = 'Greens_r')

ax.legend(title = 'Borrower Credit Rating')
plt.title('Distribution of Income Ranges and Credit Ratings')
plt.ylabel('Borrower Income Range');

From this clustered bar chart, we can see the trend of higher incomes correlate to a higher credit rating qualifying the borrower for the best (lowest) interest rates.

Having an income of $75k+ doesn't automatically guarantee the best credit ratings. I'm curious to see in the multivariate analysis what other factors play a big role in determining one's credit rating.

Conversely, it also appears that in the $0 income range, there are a high amount of "AA" loans relative to the \$1-25k income range. I hypothesize you must have other significant assets or a great history with the platform to receive the highest credit rating without any income!

In [31]:
# correlation plot 

num_vars = ['BorrowerAPR', 'ProsperScore', 'DelinquenciesLast7Years', 
            'StatedMonthlyIncome', 'AvailableBankcardCredit', 'CreditScoreRangeUpper']

           cmap = 'vlag_r', center = 0)
plt.title('Correlation Plot') 
plt.show()

No pairs exhibit any significant positive correlations, according to the correlation plot. It makes sense because better credit scores are associated with more AvailableBankcardCredit. Because borrowers with lower scores are more likely to pay higher APR, BorrowerAPR and ProsperScore are both negative. Similar to this, a higher CreditScore indicates that the borrowers are more reliable, which results in a reduced APR.

Multivariate Exploration¶

In [33]:
grid = sns.FacetGrid(data = df, col = 'ProsperRatingCombined', col_wrap = 4, size = 3)
grid.map(sns.regplot, 'BorrowerAPR', 'ProsperScore', y_jitter = 0.35, 
         scatter_kws = {'s':1},  line_kws ={'color':'red'})
grid.set_xlabels('BorrowerAPR')
grid.set_ylabels('ProsperScore')
grid.fig.set_size_inches(14,8)
plt.show();

This grid makes it easier to compare the BorrowerAPR and ProsperScore based on various letter ratings. According to the patterns, debtors with the lowest HR have the highest APR. Borrowers with an A(A) rating have reduced APRs. Based on their ratings and scores, this visualization separates several groups of people according to the APR they obtained.

Conclusions¶

Some of the relationships observed in this part of the investigation¶

Correlation plots and matrix plots from the previous plots can also be counted as part of the multivariate search. For greater efficiency, these two plots can be created early in the investigation to preview all variables and their interactions. Additionally, FacetGrid shows how each rating group differs with respect to his BorrowerAPR and ProsperScore.

From all the above visualizations created from univariate to multivariate searches, we found many variables to be negatively correlated with BorrowerAPR, but ProspoerScore yields the strongest negative relationship.
